From: Enrique Parodi Spalazzi <enrique.parodi@airbus.com>
Date: Thu, 23 Apr 2026 01:05:31 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 4/4] docs[stl]: refactor user guide for clarity and
 completeness

Editorial pass on stl.md on top of the earlier grammar-reference commit:

- Rename the document to "The Sen Type Language (STL)" and rewrite the
  opener so it no longer leans on the word "interfaces".
- Replace the Person hello-world with a TemperatureSensor example that
  showcases a static property, a writable property, a const method with
  a return type, and a confirmed event.
- Promote "Value types vs classes" to a top-level section right after
  Basic types, since it is the load-bearing concept that governs where
  every subsequent type can appear.
- Add a Literals section documenting the minimal literal syntax (no
  escape sequences, decimal-only integers, decimal-point-required
  floats).
- Add a cross-package usage example under File structure so readers
  learn how to reference types from imported packages by qualified
  name.
- Document the tag: attribute with a realistic vital/audit example
  showing how tags unlock cross-class meta-queries.
- Reword the abstract-class explanation to drop the circular phrasing
  and clarify the role of the C++ implementation.
- Tighten the variant semantics sentence so it no longer hints at a
  valueless state.
- Expand the alias example with one that aliases a struct from another
  package, matching the aliases-are-shortcuts-for-anything framing.
- Drop the historical NOTE in "Customizing the generated code" that
  described why the feature moved out of STL; that context belongs in
  git history, not the user guide.
- Fix a "per STL files" typo and reword the misleading "ASCII string"
  cell in the basic-types table.
- Remove em dashes throughout so the document matches the project's
  prose conventions.

No grammar or parser changes; documentation only.
